    • Class com.ptc.core.components.forms.DynamicRefreshInfo extends java.lang.Object implements Serializable

      serialVersionUID:
      1L

      • Serialized Fields

        • oid

          NmOid oid
          The oid of the target object of an operation. For example, a newly created object, a new object iteration, a moved object, etc.

        • location

          NmOid location
          The oid of the object on the page needing updating. For example, the folder to which a newly created object should be added, the old iteration of an updated object, the folder from which an object was moved. Meaning depends on context and action. May be the same as the "oid" attribute.

        • action

          DynamicRefreshInfo.Action action
          The action that should be taken. Must be one of the entries in the Action Enumeration:
          • UPDATE - NmCommandBean.DYNAMIC_ADD - Add oid object to page at location
          • ADD - NmCommandBean.DYNAMIC_UPD - Update location object with oid object
          • DELETE - NmCommandBean.DYNAMIC_EXPAND - Expand a tree node. Not applicable to form result processing.

    • Class com.ptc.core.meta.common.DiscreteSet extends java.lang.Object implements Serializable

      serialVersionUID:
      -6531621411425516444L

      • Serialization Methods

        • readObject

          private void readObject(java.io.ObjectInputStream in)
                 throws java.io.IOException,
                        java.lang.ClassNotFoundException
          This is sort of an equivalent to evolution support for a serializable class.

          Below I'll state in english what's happening even though its completely redundant with the code:

          Basically, you have to lie about the fields in the class rather than let java use reflection to get the field descriptors. This is done in the field com.ptc.core.meta.common.DiscreteSet#serialPersistentFields. This field claims that the class has three fields that take part in serialization, when in fact only two of them do in the current version of the class. Unless 'set' is listed as a serializable field, old instances of the class which only stored 'set' and 'negated' on the stream cannot be decoded.

          Next this method takes over the setting of the fields during deserialization. First it looks for the list on the stream. If found, it it will be used for initializing the list and the set. Otherwise, if only the set is found, then the object is an old, pre-R7 instance; there's no list in that class so the list has to be created with the set's contents in the order it returns them. If neither list or set was found, then we don't know what is going on and we have to bomb.

          Throws:
          java.io.IOException
          java.lang.ClassNotFoundException

      • Serialized Fields

        • set

          java.util.HashSet<E> set

        • list

          java.lang.Object[] list

        • negated

          boolean negated
